SIMPLE: spar
RECORDS: 5

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: spar
<hw>spar</hw> <pr>(sp⟦aum⟧r)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[AS.
<ets>spaer</ets> in <ets>spaerst⟦amac⟧n</ets> chalkstone; akin to MHG.
<ets>spar</ets>, G. <ets>spar</ets>kalk plaster.]</ety>
<fld>(Min.)</fld> <def>An old name for a nonmetallic mineral, usually
cleavable and somewhat lustrous; <as>as, calc <ex>spar</ex>, or calcite,
fluor <ex>spar</ex>, etc.</as> It was especially used in the case of the
gangue minerals of a metalliferous vein.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><mcol><col><b>Blue spar</b></col>, <col><b>Cube
spar</b></col></mcol>, <cd>etc. See under <er>Blue</er>, <er>Cube</er>,
etc.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Spar</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Spar
<hw>Spar</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[OE. <ets>sparre</ets>; akin to D.
<ets>spar</ets>, G. <ets>sparren</ets>, OHG. <ets>sparro</ets>, Dan. &
Sw. <ets>sparre</ets>, Icel. <ets>sparri</ets>; of uncertain origin.
⟦root⟧171. Cf. <er>Spar</er>, <pos>v. t.</pos> ]</ety> <sn>1.</sn>
<fld>(Naut.)</fld> <def>A general term any round piece of timber used as
a mast, yard, boom, or gaff.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <fld>(Arch.)</fld> <def>Formerly, a piece of timber, in a
general sense; -- still applied locally to rafters.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>The bar of a gate or door.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>
<rj><au>Chaucer.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Spar buoy</b></col> <fld>(Naut.)</fld>, <cd>a buoy
anchored by one end so that the other end rises above the surface of the
water.</cd> -- <col><b>Spar deck</b></col> <fld>(Naut.)</fld>, <cd>the
upper deck of a vessel; especially, in a frigate, the deck which is
continued in a straight line from the quarter-deck to the forecastle,
and on which spare spars are usually placed. See under
<er>Deck</er>.</cd> -- <col><b>Spar torpedo</b></col>
<fld>(Naut.)</fld>, <cd>a torpedo carried on the end of a spar usually
projecting from the bow of a vessel, and intended to explode upon
contact with an enemy's ships.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Spar</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Spar
<hw>Spar</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <ety>[OE. <ets>sparren</ets>, AS.
<ets>sparrian</ets>; akin to G. <ets>sperren</ets>, Icel.
<ets>sperra</ets>; from the noun. ⟦root⟧171. See <er>Spara</er> beam,
bar.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To bolt; to bar.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>
<rj><au>Chaucer.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To To supply or equip with spars, as a
vessel.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><note>⟦hand⟧ A vessel equipped with spars that are too large or too
small is said to be <xex>oversparred</xex> or
<xex>undersparred</xex>.</note>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Spar</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 4 ====
HEADWORD: Spar
<hw>Spar</hw>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos>
<conjf>Sparred</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Sparring</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[Of uncertain origin; cf. OF.
<ets>esparer</ets> to kick, F. <ets>⟦eacute⟧parer</ets>, or Icel.
<ets>sperra</ets> to stretch out the legs, to struggle.]</ety>
<sn>1.</sn> <def>To strike with the feet or spurs, as cocks
do.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To use the fists and arms scientifically in attack
or defense; to contend or combat with the fists, as for exercise or
amusement; to box.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Made believe to <qex>spar</qex> at Paul with great science.</q>
<rj><qau>Dickens.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>To contest in words; to wrangle.</def>
<mark>[Colloq.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><-- sparring partner, (Boxing) one who spars with a boxer as an
opponent for training purposes. -->⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Spar</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 5 ====
HEADWORD: Spar
<hw>Spar</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>A contest at sparring or
boxing.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>A movement of offense or defense in
boxing.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Sparable</ent>⟦br⟧
